references: Synthetic samples from the diffusion model are created by introducing slight variations to real samples through augmented noise (ΔΔ\Delta), aiming to resemble the original data closely but not identical. Synthetic samples created through diffusion, correspond one-to-one with real samples, ensuring equal quantities of both. The classifier was trained on a mix of real and synthetic data and then tested on real data alone. This approach was compared to training exclusively with real data, under the hypothesis that if the synthetic data offered no additional information, the performances would be identical. table 1 presents a comprehensive comparison of classifier performance (SVM, EEGNet, and TSception) on the DEAP dataset within a 95% confidence interval, adding robustness to the findings, under various data augmentation conditions (ΔΔ\Delta = 0.01, 0.05, 0.1). The ’Real’ column shows the baseline accuracy of each classifier when trained and tested on real data only. This serves as a reference point for evaluating the impact of synthetic data. The columns under ‘Vanilla Diffusion,’ ‘Proposed Method,’ and ‘GAN’ show the accuracy and gain (or loss) when classifiers are trained on a combination of real and synthetic data. The gain values indicate the improvement or decline in performance compared to the baseline. They refer to synthetic data generated via vanilla diffusion model, our approach, and GAN, respectively. All classifiers were tested only on real dataset.

references: In another experiment, samples comprising purely Gaussian noise, unrelated to EEG data, were generated without utilizing the diffusion model. table 2 presents the training results on a combination of real EEG samples and these Gaussian noise samples, with testing conducted on real EEG samples. The accuracy for arousal and dominance decreases slightly and the gain is negative, indicating a drop in performance. There is negligible change in the classifier’s performance for liking and valence. Using mere Gaussian noise instead of diffusion-generated samples leads to decreased classification performance due to the lack of relevant information contributing to the classifier’s training. In contrast, when using diffusion-generated data for training, the samples are closely similar to real samples, with minor variations from noise augmentation. The proposed approach enriches the classifier’s feature learning, enhancing its classification performance.
